Proposition S.1.2. Suppose $\pi$ is some distribution on $\Theta$. Assume that $\lambda_{\max }\left(\frac{\partial^{2} A\left(\theta_{0}\right)}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}}\right) \leq$ $\tilde{\beta}$ for some $\tilde{\beta}>0$. Fix $\epsilon>0$. Define the set $B\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, \epsilon\right)=\left\{p_{\theta}: K L\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)<\epsilon, V\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)<\right.$ $\epsilon\}$, where $V\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)=\operatorname{Var}_{p_{\theta_{0}}}\left[\log p_{\theta_{0}} / p_{\theta}\right]$. Then for every $\epsilon>0$ the exists $\delta=\delta(\epsilon)>0$ such that,

$$
\pi\left\{B\left(p_{\theta}, \epsilon\right)\right\}=\pi\left\{\theta \in \Theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\delta\right\}
$$

Proof. It is straightforward to establish that $K L\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)=\left\langle\theta_{0}-\theta, \mu_{0}\right\rangle+\log z(\theta)-\log z\left(\theta_{0}\right)$. Indeed, letting $T \in \mathbb{R}^{p(p+1) / 2}$ to be the vector of sufficient statistics, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
K L\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right) & =\log z(\theta)-\log z\left(\theta_{0}\right)+\int\left\langle\theta_{0}-\theta, T\right\rangle p_{\theta_{0}}(x) d x \\
& =\left\langle\theta_{0}-\theta, \mu_{0}\right\rangle+\log z(\theta)-\log z\left(\theta_{0}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\mu_{0}=\mathbb{E}_{\theta_{0}}[T]$. Furthermore,

$$
\begin{aligned}
V\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right) & =\int\left\langle\theta_{0}-\theta, T-\mu_{0}\right\rangle^{2} p_{\theta_{0}}(x) d x \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{\theta_{0}}\left[\left\langle\theta_{0}-\theta, T-\mu_{0}\right\rangle^{2}\right] \\
& =\left(\theta_{0}-\theta\right)^{\mathrm{T}} \frac{\partial^{2} \log z\left(\theta_{0}\right)}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}}\left(\theta_{0}-\theta\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Write $A(\theta)=\log z(\theta)$ and $A\left(\theta_{0}\right)=\log z\left(\theta_{0}\right)$. It is well known that $A(\theta)$ is convex and has derivatives of all orders (Wainwright et al., 2008, Proposition 3.1). Also, by assumption $\lambda_{\max }\left(\frac{\partial^{2} A\left(\theta_{0}\right)}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}}\right) \leq \tilde{\beta}$ which implies there exists $L>0$ such that $\left\|\nabla A\left(\theta_{1}\right)-\nabla A\left(\theta_{2}\right)\right\|_{2} \leq$ $L\left\|\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\right\|_{2}$ for all $\theta_{1}, \theta_{2} \in \Theta$. Thus, standard convex analysis (Boyd and Vandenberghe, 2004) implies that:

$$
\left|A\left(\theta_{1}\right)-A\left(\theta_{2}\right)-\nabla A\left(\theta_{2}\right)^{\mathrm{T}}\left(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\right)\right| \leq \frac{L}{2}\left\|\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\right\|_{2}^{2}
$$

Since, $K L\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)=\left\langle\theta_{0}-\theta, \mu_{0}\right\rangle+A(\theta)-A\left(\theta_{0}\right)$ and $\lambda_{\min }\left(\frac{\partial^{2} A\left(\theta_{0}\right)}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}}\right) \geq \beta$, we have that:

$$
\frac{\beta}{2}\left\|\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\right\|_{2}^{2} \leq K L\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right) \leq \frac{L}{2}\left\|\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\right\|_{2}^{2}
$$

which proves the result. A similar argument applies to $V\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)$.

# S.1.5 Proof of Theorem 6.4 

Define the matrix $S=\left(S_{j k}\right)$ where $S_{j k}=\sum_{i=1}^{n} T\left(X_{i j}, X_{i k}\right)$ if $j \neq k$ and $S_{j j}=\sum_{i=1}^{n} T\left(X_{i j}\right)$. Then $\ell(\theta)=\sum_{i=1}^{n} q_{\theta}\left(X_{i}\right)-n A(\theta)=\operatorname{tr}(\theta S)-n A(\theta)$. The $\ell_{1}$-penalized estimator is defined as the minimizer of $-\ell(\theta)+\lambda\|\theta\|_{1}=n A(\theta)-\operatorname{tr}(\theta S)+\lambda\|\theta\|_{1}$. Let

$$
\begin{aligned}
Q(\theta) & =n A(\theta)-\operatorname{tr}(\theta S)+\lambda\|\theta\|_{1}-n A\left(\theta_{0}\right)+\operatorname{tr}\left(\theta_{0} S\right)-\lambda\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1} \\
& =n\left[A(\theta)-A\left(\theta_{0}\right)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left[\left(\theta-\theta_{0}\right)\left(S-\mu_{0}\right)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left[\left(\theta-\theta_{0}\right) \mu_{0}\right]+\lambda\left[\|\theta\|_{1}-\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Then, the $\ell_{1}$ penalized estimate minimizes $Q(\theta)$. Define $\Delta=\theta-\theta_{0}$ and $G(\Delta)=Q\left(\theta_{0}+\Delta\right)$. Equivalently, we want to minimize $G(\Delta)$ with respect to $\Delta$. First, note that for any $\alpha \in(0,1)$ and $\theta_{1}, \theta_{2} \in \Theta$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\alpha Q\left(\theta_{1}\right)= & n \alpha\left[A\left(\theta_{1}\right)-A\left(\theta_{0}\right)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left[\alpha\left(\theta_{1}-\theta_{0}\right)\left(S-\mu_{0}\right)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left[\alpha\left(\theta_{1}-\theta_{0}\right) \mu_{0}\right] \\
& +\lambda \alpha\left[\left\|\theta_{1}\right\|_{1}-\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1}\right] \\
(1-\alpha) Q\left(\theta_{2}\right)= & n(1-\alpha)\left[A\left(\theta_{2}\right)-A\left(\theta_{0}\right)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left[(1-\alpha)\left(\theta_{2}-\theta_{0}\right)\left(S-\mu_{0}\right)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left[(1-\alpha)\left(\theta_{2}-\theta_{0}\right) \mu_{0}\right] \\
& +\lambda(1-\alpha)\left[\left\|\theta_{1}\right\|_{1}-\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

This implies that if $\theta^{\star}=\alpha \theta_{1}+(1-\alpha) \theta_{2}$ then,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\alpha Q\left(\theta_{1}\right)+(1-\alpha) Q\left(\theta_{2}\right) & \geq n\left[A\left(\theta^{\star}\right)-A(\theta)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left(\left(\theta^{\star}-\theta_{0}\right)\left(S-\mu_{0}\right)\right)-\operatorname{tr}\left(\left(\theta^{\star}-\theta_{0}\right) \mu_{0}\right) \\
& +\lambda\left[\left\|\theta^{\star}\right\|_{1}-\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1}\right] \\
& =Q\left(\theta^{\star}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

by triangle inequality and since $A(\theta)$ is convex. Similarly, if $\Delta_{1}=\theta_{1}-\theta_{0}$ and $\Delta_{2}=\theta_{2}-\theta_{0}$, then $\alpha G\left(\Delta_{1}\right)+(1-\alpha) G\left(\Delta_{2}\right) \geq G\left(\Delta^{\star}\right)$ where $\Delta^{\star}=\theta^{\star}-\theta_{0}$. Thus, $G(\Delta)$ is convex and $G(0)=0$. Hence, if $\hat{\Delta}=\inf _{\Delta} G(\Delta)$, then $G(\hat{\Delta}) \leq 0$.

Now, $G(\Delta)=n\left[A\left(\theta_{0}+\Delta\right)-A\left(\theta_{0}\right)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left[\Delta\left(S-\mu_{0}\right)\right]-\operatorname{tr}\left(\Delta \mu_{0}\right)+\lambda\left[\left\|\theta_{0}+\Delta\right\|_{1}-\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1}\right]$.

A Taylor expansion of $A\left(\theta_{0}+\Delta\right)-A\left(\theta_{0}\right)$ yields

$$
\begin{aligned}
A\left(\theta_{0}+\Delta\right)-A\left(\theta_{0}\right) & =\operatorname{tr}\left(\nabla A\left(\theta_{0}\right) \Delta\right) \\
& +\tilde{\Delta}^{\top}\left[\int_{0}^{1}(1-v)\left\{\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial v^{2}} A\left(\theta_{0}+v \Delta\right)\right\} d v\right] \tilde{\Delta}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\tilde{\Delta}=\operatorname{vec}(\Delta) \in \mathbb{R}^{p^{2}}$. Here, we adopt the convention that for a matrix-valued function (with matrix arguments) $f: \mathbb{R}^{d_{1} \times d_{2}} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{d_{3} \times d_{4}}, d f(A)$ is a matrix of order $d_{1} d_{3} \times d_{2} d_{4}$ with elements

$$
d f(A)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{d f}{A_{11}} & \cdots & \frac{d f}{A_{1, d_{2}}} \\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots \\
\frac{d f}{A_{d_{1}, 1}} & \cdots & \frac{d f}{A_{d_{1}, d_{2}}}
\end{array}\right)
$$

In particular, since $\nabla A(\theta) \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times p}$, we have that $\frac{\partial^{2} A(\theta)}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{T}} \in \mathbb{R}^{p^{2} \times p^{2}}$.
Thus $G(\Delta)=n \tilde{\Delta}^{\top}\left[\int_{0}^{1}(1-v) \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial v^{2}} A\left(\theta_{0}+v \Delta\right) d v\right] \tilde{\Delta}-\operatorname{tr}\left[\Delta\left(S-\mu_{0}\right)\right]+\lambda\left[\left\|\theta_{0}+\Delta\right\|_{1}-\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1}\right]$. That is, $G(\Delta)=T_{1}-T_{2}+T_{3}$. Let $\mathbf{S}=\left\{j \leq k: \theta_{0, j k} \neq 0, j, k=1, \ldots, p\right\}$. We next work with each term separately. We have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left|T_{2}\right|=\left|\operatorname{tr}\left[\Delta\left(S-\mu_{0}\right)\right]\right| & \leq\left|\sum \sum_{j \leq k}\left(S_{j k}-\mu_{0, j k}\right) \Delta_{j k}\right| \\
& \leq\left|\sum_{j \leq k: \delta_{0, j k}=0}\left(S_{j k}-\mu_{0, j k}\right) \Delta_{j k}\right|+\left|\sum_{j \leq k: \delta_{0, j k} \neq 0}\left(S_{j k}-\mu_{0, j k}\right) \Delta_{j k}\right| \\
& \leq \max _{\mathbf{S}^{c}}\left|S_{j k}-\mu_{0, j k}\right|\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}^{c}}\right\|_{1}+\sqrt{s} \max _{\mathbf{S}}\left|S_{j k}-\mu_{0, j k}\right|\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}}\right\|_{F}
\end{aligned}
$$

where the second bound comes from Cauchy-Schwarz inequality. From Proposition S.1.1, and the union bound we have that with probability at least $1-2 e^{-C_{1} \log p}, \max _{j \leq k} \mid S_{j k}-$ $\mu_{0, j k} \mid \leq C_{1} \sqrt{\log p / n}$ for some $C, C_{1}>0$. Thus we have with probability tending to 1 ,

$$
\left|T_{2}\right| \leq C_{1} \sqrt{\frac{\log p}{n}}\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}^{c}}\right\|_{1}+C_{1} \sqrt{\frac{s \log p}{n}}\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}}\right\|_{F}
$$

Next, we work with $T_{3}=\lambda\left[\left\|\theta_{0}+\Delta\right\|_{1}-\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1}\right]$. Clearly, $\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{1}=\left\|\theta_{0 \mathbf{S}}\right\|_{1}$ and $\left\|\theta_{0}+\Delta\right\|_{1}=$

$\left\|\theta_{0 \mathbf{S}}+\Delta_{S}\right\|_{1}+\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}^{c}}\right\|_{1}$. Thus, by triangle inequality

$$
T_{3} \geq \lambda\left(\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}^{c}}\right\|_{1}-\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}}\right\|_{1}\right)
$$

Set $\lambda=\frac{C_{1}}{\epsilon} \sqrt{\frac{\log p}{n}}$ for some $0<\epsilon<1$. Then since $\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}}\right\|_{1} \leq \sqrt{s}\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}}\right\|_{F}$, we have,

$$
T_{3} \geq \frac{C_{1}}{\epsilon} \sqrt{\frac{\log p}{n}}\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}^{c}}\right\|_{1}-\frac{C_{1}}{\epsilon} \sqrt{\frac{s \log p}{n}}\left\|\Delta_{\mathbf{S}}\right\|_{F}
$$

Finally, for $T_{1}$ we have for $\Delta \in \Theta_{n}(M)=\left\{\Delta: \Delta=\Delta^{\mathrm{T}},\|\Delta\|_{F}=M r_{n}\right\}$

$$
\begin{aligned}
T_{1} & =n \tilde{\Delta}^{\mathrm{T}}\left[\int_{0}^{1}(1-v) \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial v^{2}} A\left(\theta_{0}+v \Delta\right) d v\right] \tilde{\Delta} \\
& \geq \lambda_{\min }\left(\int_{0}^{1}(1-v) \frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial v^{2}} A\left(\theta_{0}+v \Delta\right) d v\right)\|\Delta\|_{F}^{2} \\
& \geq\|\Delta\|_{F}^{2} \int_{0}^{1}(1-v) \lambda_{\min }\left(\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial v^{2}} A\left(\theta_{0}+v \Delta\right)\right) d v \\
& \geq\|\Delta\|_{F}^{2} \min _{0 \leq v \leq 1} \lambda_{\min }\left(\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A\left(\theta_{0}+v \Delta\right)\right) \int_{0}^{1}(1-v) d v \\
& \geq \frac{1}{2}\|\Delta\|_{F}^{2} \min \left[\lambda_{\min }\left(\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A\left(\theta_{0}+\bar{\Delta}\right)\right):\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{F} \leq M r_{n}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

In order to work with $\lambda_{\min }\left(\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A\left(\theta_{0}+\bar{\Delta}\right)\right)$, we next consider a Taylor expansion of $\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A(\theta)$. For a matrix $P,\|P\|_{2}=\sup _{\|x\|_{2}=1}\|P x\|_{2}$. We note here that $\frac{\partial^{2} A(\theta)}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}}: \Xi \rightarrow$ $\mathbb{R}^{p^{2} \times p^{2}}$, where $\Xi=\Theta \times \Theta$. Elements of $\Xi$ are of the form $\theta \otimes \theta$. Let $\xi_{0}=\theta_{0} \otimes \theta_{0}$. Then, a $\tilde{\Delta}$ perturbation in $\theta_{0}$ leads to the following perturbation in $\xi_{0}: \xi_{\tilde{\Delta}}=\left(\theta_{0}+\bar{\Delta}\right) \otimes$ $\left(\theta_{0}+\bar{\Delta}\right)=\xi_{0}+\theta_{0} \otimes \tilde{\Delta}+\tilde{\Delta} \otimes \theta_{0}+\tilde{\Delta} \otimes \tilde{\Delta}=\xi_{0}+\underline{\Delta}$, say. Moreover, $\left\|\xi_{\tilde{\Delta}}-\xi_{0}\right\|_{2}=$ $\|\underline{\Delta}\|_{2} \leq 2\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{2}+\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{2}^{2}$, where we have used the fact that $\|A \otimes B\|_{2}=\|A\|_{2}\|B\|_{2}$. Similarly, $\left\|\xi_{\tilde{\Delta}}-\xi_{0}\right\|_{F}=\|\underline{\Delta}\|_{F} \leq 2\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{F}+\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{F}^{2}$, since $\|A B\|_{F} \leq\|A\|_{2}\|B\|_{F}$. Hence, $\left\|\xi_{\tilde{\Delta}}-\xi_{0}\right\|_{2}=O\left(r_{n}\right)$ and $\left\|\xi_{\tilde{\Delta}}-\xi_{0}\right\|_{F}=O\left(r_{n}\right)$ since by assumption $\left\|\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\bar{\beta}$. Then, a Taylor expansion of $G\left(\xi_{0}+\underline{\Delta}\right)$ around $\xi_{0}$ (Vetter, 1973, Equation (24)) yields:

$$
G\left(\xi_{0}+\underline{\Delta}\right)=G\left(\xi_{0}\right)+D_{\xi_{0}^{T}}[\operatorname{tr}(\underline{\Delta} G(\xi))]+R_{\xi_{0}}
$$

where $R_{\xi_{0}}^{p^{2} \times p^{2}}$ is a matrix such that $\left\|R_{\xi_{0}}\right\|_{F}=o\left(\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{F}\right)$, which follows from the property of Taylor's theorem and analytical nature of $A(\theta)$ for all $\theta \in \Theta$. Thus, we have that

$G\left(\xi_{0}+\Delta\right)=G\left(\xi_{0}\right)+H$, where $H=D_{\xi_{0}^{\mathrm{T}}}[t r(\Delta G(\xi))]+R_{\xi_{0}}$, and $\|H\|_{2} \leq\left\|D_{\xi_{0}^{\mathrm{T}}}[t r(\Delta G(\xi))]\right\|_{2}+$ $\left\|R_{\xi_{0}}\right\|_{2} \leq C\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{2}+\left\|R_{\xi_{0}}\right\|_{2}$ for some positive constant $C>0$ by the regularity assumption. Hence, $\|H\|_{2}=O\left(r_{n}\right)$. Due to Weyl's inequality, we then have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left|\lambda_{\min }\left(\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A\left(\theta_{0}+\bar{\Delta}\right)\right)-\lambda_{\min }\left(\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A\left(\theta_{0}\right)\right)\right| \\
& \leq\left\|\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A\left(\theta_{0}+\bar{\Delta}\right)-\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A\left(\theta_{0}\right)\right\|_{2} \\
& \leq C r_{n}
\end{aligned}
$$

for some $C>0$. Since $\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{F} \leq M r_{n}$ and $M r_{n} \rightarrow 0$ as $n \rightarrow \infty$ we have that,

$$
\lambda_{\min }\left(\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial \theta \partial \theta^{\mathrm{T}}} A\left(\theta_{0}+\bar{\Delta}\right):\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{F} \leq M r_{n}\right) \geq \frac{\beta}{2}
$$

Putting all the pieces together, we obtain,

$$
\begin{aligned}
G(\Delta) & \geq \frac{n \beta}{4}\|\Delta\|_{F}^{2}+C_{1} \sqrt{\frac{\log p}{n}}\left\|\Delta_{S^{c}}\right\|_{1}\left(\frac{1}{\epsilon}-1\right)-C_{1} \sqrt{\frac{s \log p}{n}}\left\|\Delta_{S}\right\|_{F}\left(1+\frac{1}{\epsilon}\right) \\
& \geq \frac{n \beta}{4}\|\Delta\|_{F}^{2}-C_{1} \sqrt{\frac{s \log p}{n}}\left\|\Delta_{S}\right\|_{F}\left(1+\frac{1}{\epsilon}\right)>0
\end{aligned}
$$

since $0<\epsilon<1$, and the second term in the last line of the above display is $O(s \log p / n)$.
Hence, we have argued that if $\hat{\Delta}$ is the minimizer of $G(\Delta)$ then $G(\hat{\Delta}) \leq 0$ and $\inf \{G(\Delta)$ : $\Delta \in \Theta_{n}(M)\}>0$, then $\hat{\Delta}$ must be inside the ball $\Theta_{n}(M)$, i.e. $\|\bar{\Delta}\|_{F} \leq M r_{n}$.

# S.1.6 Proof of Theorem 6.5 

To establish the posterior concentration rate result, we follow the standard route of sufficient conditions established by Ghosal and Van der Vaart (2017, Chapter 8). Define $B\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, \epsilon\right)=$ $\left\{p_{\theta}: K L\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)<\epsilon, V\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)<\epsilon\right\}$ and $\mathcal{P}=\left\{p_{\theta}: \theta \in \Theta\right\}$. Equip $\mathcal{P}$ with the Hellinger metric which we write as $H$ (the choice of the metric can is flexible). To be precise, define the squared Hellinger distance between two probability distributions having densities $p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$ with respect to the Lebesgue measure as: $H^{2}\left(p_{1}, p_{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2} \int\left(\sqrt{p_{1}(x)}-\sqrt{p_{2}(x)}\right)^{2} d x$.

Now suppose $p_{1}(x)=q_{\theta_{1}}(x) / z\left(\theta_{1}\right)$ and $p_{2}(x)=q_{\theta_{2}}(x) / z\left(\theta_{2}\right)$ where $\theta_{1}, \theta_{2} \in \Theta$. Then, straightforward calculations yield:

$$
H^{2}\left(p_{1}, p_{2}\right)=1-\frac{z\left(\frac{\theta_{1}+\theta_{2}}{2}\right)}{\sqrt{z\left(\theta_{1}\right) z\left(\theta_{2}\right)}}
$$

Furthermore, by Pinsker's inequality:

$$
H^{2}\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right) \leq \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \sqrt{K L\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)} \leq C\left\|\theta_{0}-\theta\right\|_{2}
$$

for some $C>0$, in the light of Proposition S.1.2. The conditions for the posterior distribution $\pi(\theta \mid \mathbf{X})$ to contract at the rate $\epsilon_{n}$ are the following:

1. Sufficient prior mass: $\pi\left\{B\left(p_{\theta_{0}, \epsilon_{n}}\right)\right\} \geq e^{-C n \epsilon_{n}^{2}}$.
2. Metric entropy: there exists a partition of $\mathcal{P}=\mathcal{P}_{1} \cup \mathcal{P}_{2}$ such that $\log \left(\xi \epsilon_{n}, \mathcal{P}_{1}, d\right) \leq n \epsilon_{n}^{2}$.
3. Small support on $\mathcal{P}_{2}$ : prior support on $\mathcal{P}_{2}$ is such that $\pi\left(\mathcal{P}_{2}\right) \leq e^{-(C+4) n \epsilon_{n}^{2}}$.

The above three conditions imply that $\pi\left(\theta: H^{2}\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right) \geq M_{n} \epsilon_{n} \mid \mathbf{X}\right) \rightarrow 0$ in $P_{\theta_{0}}$-probability as $n \rightarrow \infty$ for every $M_{n} \rightarrow \infty$. We show that in our case these conditions hold with $\epsilon_{n}=\bar{\epsilon}_{n}=\sqrt{s \log ^{2} p / n}$.
(1) Prior mass: The vectorized data generating parameter $\operatorname{vech}\left(\theta_{0}\right) \in \Theta \subset \mathbb{R}^{p(p+1) / 2}$. By Assumption 6.2, $\Theta$ is open, hence there exists $\epsilon>0$ such that $\left\{\theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\epsilon\right\} \subset \Theta$. Moreover, from Proposition S.1.2, we have:

$$
\pi\left\{B\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, \epsilon\right)\right\}=\pi\left\{\theta \in \Theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\delta(\epsilon)\right\}
$$

Since the prior distribution is a truncation of the prior on $\mathbb{R}^{p(p+1) / 2}$, we also have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\pi\left\{\theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\epsilon\right\} & =\frac{\pi_{L}\left\{\theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\epsilon\right\}}{\pi_{L}(\Theta)} \\
& \geq \pi_{L}\left\{\theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\epsilon\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

since $\pi_{L}(\Theta) \leq 1$. Next, we obtain a lower bound of $\pi_{L}\left\{\theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\bar{\epsilon}_{n}\right\}$ where $\bar{\epsilon}_{n}=$

$\left\{\left(s \log ^{2} p\right) / n\right\}^{1 / 2}$. We will show for $\theta, \theta_{0} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$, and $\theta_{0}$ having $s$ non-zero entries,

$$
\pi_{L}\left\{\theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\sqrt{\frac{s \log ^{2} p}{n}}\right\} \geq \pi_{L}\left\{\theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\sqrt{\frac{s \log p}{n}}\right\} \geq e^{-C n \ell_{n}^{2}}
$$

The result then applies to our context where $\theta_{0}, \theta \in \mathbb{R}^{p(p+1) / 2}$. Define $S=\left\{j:\left|\theta_{0 j}\right| \neq 0\right\}$. Set $\delta=\sqrt{(s \log p) / n}$. We then have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}\left[\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\delta\right] & \geq \mathbb{P}\left[\left\|\theta_{S}-\theta_{0 S}\right\|_{2}<\frac{\delta}{2}\right] \mathbb{P}\left[\left\|\theta_{S^{c}}\right\|_{2}<\frac{\delta}{2}\right] \\
& \geq \prod_{j \in S} \mathbb{P}\left[\left|\theta_{j}-\theta_{0 j}\right|<\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{s}}\right] \int_{I_{\lambda}} \mathbb{P}\left[\left\|\theta_{S^{c}}\right\|_{2}<\frac{\delta}{2} \mid \lambda \in I_{\lambda}\right] \pi(\lambda) d \lambda
\end{aligned}
$$

where $I_{\lambda}=\left[\lambda_{1}, \lambda_{2}\right]$ with $\lambda_{1}=\sqrt{\frac{n p \log p}{s}}$ and $\lambda_{2}=2 \lambda_{1}$. We next focus on the conditional probability:

$$
\mathbb{P}\left[\left\|\theta_{0 S^{c}}\right\|_{2} \leq \frac{\delta}{2} \mid \lambda \in I_{\lambda}\right] \geq \prod_{j \notin S} \mathbb{P}\left[\left|\theta_{j}\right|<\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{p}} \mid \lambda \in I_{\lambda}\right]
$$

First, we handle the term $\mathbb{P}\left[\left|\theta_{j}\right|<\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{p}} \mid \lambda \in I_{\lambda}\right]$. Recall, if the random variable $X$ is sub-exponential distribution with parameters $\left(\nu^{2}, \rho\right)$, then,

$$
\mathbb{P}[|X-\mu| \geq t] \leq \begin{cases}2 e^{-\frac{t^{2}}{2 \nu^{2}}}, & \text { if } 0<t \leq \frac{\nu^{2}}{\rho} \\ 2 e^{-\frac{t}{2 \rho}}, & \text { if } t>\frac{\nu^{2}}{\rho}\end{cases}
$$

Here $\theta_{j} \mid \lambda \sim \operatorname{Laplace}(1 / \lambda)$, and the Laplace distribution is sub-exponential with $\nu=2 / \lambda$ and $\rho=2 / \lambda$. Set $t=\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{p}}=\frac{1}{2} \sqrt{\frac{s \log p}{n p}}$ in (S.4) and note that $\nu^{2} / \rho=2 / \lambda$. Thus, for any $\lambda>4 \sqrt{\frac{n p}{s \log p}}$ we have:

$$
\mathbb{P}\left[\left|\theta_{j}\right|<\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{p}} \mid \lambda\right] \geq 1-2 e^{-\frac{\delta \lambda}{4 \sqrt{p}}}
$$

Specifically, for any $\lambda \in I_{\lambda}$ we get,

$$
\mathbb{P}\left[\left|\theta_{j}\right|<\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{p}} \mid \lambda \in I_{\lambda}\right] \geq 1-2 e^{-\frac{\delta \lambda}{4 \sqrt{p}}} \geq 1-2 e^{\frac{\delta \lambda_{1}}{4 \sqrt{p}}}=1-2 e^{-\frac{1}{4} \log p}
$$

Thus, for some $C>0, \mathbb{P}\left[\left|\theta_{j}\right|<\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{p}} \mid \lambda\right] \geq e^{-C \log p}$ for some $C>0$. We also have $\mathbb{P}[\lambda \in$ $\left.I_{\lambda}\right]=\mathbb{P}\left[\lambda>\lambda_{1}\right]-\mathbb{P}\left[\lambda>\lambda_{2}\right]$. Next, we record the following upper and lower bounds for the incomplete Gamma function (Pinelis, 2020),

$$
\frac{x^{a} e^{-x}(x-a-1)}{(x-a)^{2}+a} \leq \Gamma(a, x)=\int_{x}^{\infty} t^{a-1} e^{-t} d t \leq \frac{x^{a} e^{-x}}{x-a}
$$

Also, we have $(a / e)^{a-1} \leq \Gamma(a) \leq(a / 2)^{a-1}$. Set $\alpha=a_{\lambda}$ and $\beta=b_{\lambda}$. Thus,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}\left(\lambda \in I_{\lambda}\right) & =\frac{\beta^{\alpha}}{\Gamma(\alpha)} \Gamma\left(\alpha, \beta \lambda_{1}\right)-\frac{\beta^{\alpha}}{\Gamma(\alpha)} \Gamma\left(\alpha, 2 \beta \lambda_{1}\right) \\
& =e^{\log \beta} e^{-(\alpha-1) \log \alpha} e^{(\alpha-1) \log 2} \Gamma\left(\alpha, \beta \lambda_{1}\right)-e^{\log \beta} e^{-(\alpha-1) \log \alpha} e^{(\alpha-1)} \Gamma\left(\alpha, 2 \beta \lambda_{1}\right) \\
& \geq e^{\log \beta} e^{-(\alpha-1) \log \alpha} e^{K(\alpha-1)}\left(\beta \lambda_{1}\right)^{\alpha} e^{-C \beta \lambda_{1}}, \quad \text { for } \alpha=O\left(\beta \lambda_{1}\right) \\
& =e^{\log \beta} e^{-(\alpha-1) \log \alpha} e^{(\alpha-1) \log 2} e^{\alpha \log \beta \lambda_{1}} e^{-C \beta \lambda_{1}} \\
& \geq e^{-C \beta \lambda_{1}} \geq e^{-C s \log p}
\end{aligned}
$$

for $\beta=O\left(s \sqrt{\frac{s \log p}{n p}}\right)$. Hence, we have that,

$$
\int_{I_{\lambda}} \mathbb{P}\left[\left\|\theta_{S^{c}}\right\|_{2}<\frac{\delta}{2} \mid \lambda \in I_{\lambda}\right] \pi(\lambda) d \lambda \geq e^{-C s \log p}
$$

for some $C>0$. We now handle the term $\mathbb{P}\left[\left|\theta_{j}-\theta_{0 j}\right|<\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{s}}\right]$. Since $\lambda \sim \operatorname{Gamma}(\alpha, \beta)$, marginal density of $\theta_{j}$ is:

$$
f\left(\theta_{j}\right)=\frac{\beta^{\alpha}}{2 \Gamma(\alpha)} \frac{\Gamma(\alpha+1)}{\left(\left|\theta_{j}\right|+\beta\right)^{\alpha+1}}=\frac{\alpha \beta^{\alpha}}{2\left(\left|\theta_{j}\right|+\beta\right)^{\alpha+1}}
$$

Let $A=\left\{\theta_{j}:\left|\theta_{j}-\theta_{0 j}\right| \leq \delta^{\star}, j \in S\right\}$ where $\delta^{\star}=\frac{\delta}{2 \sqrt{s}}$. We have for $\alpha, \beta$ as chosen above

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}\left[\theta_{j} \in A\right] & =\int_{A} \frac{\alpha \beta^{\alpha}}{2\left(\left|\theta_{j}\right|+\beta\right)^{\alpha+1}} d \theta_{j} \\
& \geq e^{-\log 2} e^{\alpha \log \beta} e^{\log \alpha} e^{\log \delta^{\star}} e^{-(\alpha+1)\left(\left|\theta_{0 j}\right|+\delta^{\star}+\beta\right)} \\
& \geq e^{-C \alpha \log \left(\frac{1}{\beta}\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

which establishes that $\pi_{L}\left\{\theta:\left\|\theta-\theta_{0}\right\|_{2}<\delta\right\}>e^{-C n \varepsilon_{n}^{2}}$.
(2) Metric entropy: Due to the relation between the Hellinger metric and the Eu-

clidean balls, the metric entropy of the set of densities $\mathcal{P}=\left\{p_{\theta}: \theta \in \Theta\right\}$ can be studied using $\left\|\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}\right\|_{2}$. Define the following sieve on $\mathcal{P}$ :

$$
\mathcal{P}_{n}=\left\{\theta \in \Theta: \sum \mathbb{1}\left\{\left|\theta_{j}\right|>\delta_{n}\right\} \leq C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2},\|\theta\|_{2} \leq B\right\}

where $B$ is a sufficiently large number to be chosen later and $\delta_{n}=s \bar{\epsilon}_{n} /(\sqrt{p \log p})$. Arguments similar to Bhattacharya et al. (2015, Theorem 3.1) establish that:

$$
\log \mathcal{N}\left(\xi \bar{\epsilon}_{n}, \mathcal{P}_{n},\|\cdot\|_{2}\right) \leq C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2}
$$

where $\xi>0$ is a positive number, $C$ is a positive constant and $\mathcal{N}(\epsilon, \mathcal{A},\|\cdot\|)$ denotes the $\epsilon$-covering number of the metric space $(\mathcal{A},\|\cdot\|)$.
(3) Prior support on $\mathcal{P}_{2}$ : Next, we work with the (unrestricted) prior probability of the complement sieve, that is, $\pi_{L}\left(\mathcal{P}_{n}^{c}\right)$. We have that:

$$
\pi_{L}\left(\mathcal{P}_{n}^{c}\right) \leq \mathbb{P}\left(N \geq C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2}+1\right)+\pi_{L}\left(\|\theta\|_{2}>B\right)

where $N$ is the random variable denoting the number of elements in a $p(p+1) / 2$-dimensional vector with marginal distribution $p(\theta)=\alpha \beta^{\alpha} /[2(|\theta|+\beta)^{(\alpha+1)}]$ exceeds $\delta_{n}$ in absolute value. $$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}\left(N \geq C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2}+1\right) & \leq 1-\Phi\left\{\left(2 p^{\star} H\left[\nu, C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2} / p^{\star}\right]\right)^{1 / 2}\right\} \\
& \leq(2 \pi)^{-1 / 2}\left(p^{\star} H\left[\nu, C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2} / p^{\star}\right]\right)^{1 / 2} \exp \left\{\left(p^{\star} H\left[\nu, C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2} / p^{\star}\right]\right)^{1 / 2}\right\}
\end{aligned}

where

$$
p^{\star} H\left[\nu, C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2} / p^{\star}\right]=C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2} \log \left(\frac{C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2}}{p^{\star} \nu}\right)+\left(p^{\star}-C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2}\right) \log \left(\frac{p^{\star}-C n \bar{\epsilon}_{n}^{2}}{p^{\star}-p^{\star} \nu}\right)

Recall $\alpha=O(s \log p)$ and $\beta=O(s \sqrt{s \log p / n p})=O\left(s \bar{\epsilon}_{n} / \sqrt{p \log p}\right)$, so that $\delta_{n} / \beta=O(1)$.

We shall show that this probability is upper bounded by $p^{-\gamma}$ for some $\gamma>0$. Indeed,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}\left(|\theta|>\delta_{n}\right) & =2 \int_{\delta_{n}}^{\infty} p(\theta) d \theta \\
& =\int_{\delta_{n}}^{\infty} \frac{\alpha \beta^{\alpha}}{(\theta+\alpha)^{\alpha+1}} d \theta \\
& =\frac{\alpha}{\alpha+2} \frac{1}{\left(1+\delta_{n} / \beta\right)^{\alpha+2}} \beta^{-2} \\
& \approx \beta^{-2} e^{-C(\alpha+2) \log 2} \leq p^{-\gamma}
\end{aligned}
$$

for some $\gamma>0$. Finally, we have,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\pi_{L}\left(\|\theta\|_{2}>B\right) & \leq \pi_{L}\left(\|\theta\|_{1}>B\right) \\
& =\int \mathbb{P}\left[\|\theta\|_{1}>B \mid \lambda\right] p(\lambda) d \lambda \\
& =\int \mathbb{P}[Y>B \mid \lambda] p(\lambda) d \lambda, \quad Y=\sum_{j=1}^{p(p+1) / 2}\left|\theta_{j}\right| \\
& =\int \mathbb{P}\left[\frac{2 Y}{\lambda}>\frac{2 B}{\lambda} \mid \lambda\right] p(\lambda) d \lambda=\int \mathbb{P}\left[\chi_{p(p+1)}^{2}>\frac{2 B}{\lambda} \mid \lambda\right] p(\lambda) d \lambda
\end{aligned}
$$

where we have used the fact that if $\theta_{j} \mid \lambda \stackrel{\text { iid }}{\sim} \operatorname{Laplace}(1 / \lambda)$ for $j=1, \ldots, p$, then $(2 / \lambda) \sum_{j}\left|\theta_{j}\right| \sim$ $\chi_{2 p}^{2}$. Hence, by Markov's inequality, we obtain,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\pi_{L}\left(\|\theta\|_{2}>B\right) & \leq \int \frac{p(p+1)}{(2 B / \lambda)} g(\lambda) d \lambda \\
& =\frac{p(p+1)}{2 B} \frac{\alpha}{\beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

with $\alpha / \beta=O(\sqrt{n p s \log p})$. Hence, setting $B=O(\sqrt{n p s \log p}) e^{k n \ell_{n}^{2}}$ for some large positive constant $k$, we obtain that $\pi_{L}\left(\|\theta\|_{2}>B\right) \leq e^{-C n \ell_{n}^{2}}$ for some $C>0$. Finally, since by assumption $\pi_{L}(\Theta) \geq e^{-K \log p}$ for some $K>0$, we have the desired result.

# S.1.7 Proof of Theorem 6.6 

Recall the proposed estimator of $\nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)$ defined as $T_{N}(\theta)=T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta) / T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta)$. Next, consider the following sequence of iterates

$$
\begin{aligned}
\theta^{(t+1)}= & \theta^{(t)}+\gamma_{t}\left[\nabla g\left(\mathbf{v} ; \theta^{(t)}, \theta^{(t)}\right)-T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right] \\
= & \theta^{(t)}+\gamma_{t}\left[\nabla g\left(\mathbf{v} ; \theta^{(t)}, \theta^{(t)}\right)-\nabla \log z\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right]+\gamma_{t}\left[\nabla \log z\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)-\mathbb{E}\left\{T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right\}\right] \\
& +\gamma_{t}\left[\mathbb{E}\left\{T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right\}-T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right] \\
= & \theta^{(t)}+\gamma_{t} m\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)+\gamma_{t} R_{t}+\gamma_{t} E_{t}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $m\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)=\left[\nabla_{\theta} \log z\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)-\mathbb{E}\left\{T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right\}\right], R_{t}=\left[\nabla_{\theta} \log z\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)-\mathbb{E}\left\{T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right\}\right]$, and $E_{t}=\left[\mathbb{E}\left\{T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right\}-T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right) \mid \mathcal{F}_{t}\right]$, where $\mathcal{F}_{t}$ is the filtration at step $t$. Since construction of $T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta_{t}\right)$ only requires knowledge of $\theta^{(t)}$, this error term is conditionally independent of $\theta^{(0)} \ldots, \theta^{(t-1)}$ given $\theta^{(t)}$. In stochastic approximation literature (Robbins and Monro, 1951; Delyon et al., 1999), the term $m(\theta)$ is known as the mean-field of the algorithm, the random variables $R_{t}$ can be thought of vanishingly small remainder or bias terms and $E_{t}$ is a random error with mean 0 . Furthermore, we allow the number of Monte Carlo samples to increase with the iterations. This makes the remainder term $R_{t}$ to converge to 0 as the number of iterations increase. In the following series of steps, we establish some key properties about the estimator $T_{N}(\theta)$ which will be key in establishing the theorem.
(A) The sequence of functions $\left\{\mathbf{T}_{\mathbf{N}}(\theta)_{\mathbf{N} \geq 1}\right\}$ is equicontinuous in $\boldsymbol{\Theta}$ : By the mean value theorem, it is enough to show that there exists $C>0$ such that:

$$
\left\|\nabla_{\theta} T_{N}(\theta)\right\|_{F}<C
$$

for all $N \geq 1$. We have,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\nabla T_{N}(\theta)=T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta) \nabla T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta)-\nabla T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta) \nabla T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta) \\
\text { i.e., }\left\|\nabla T_{N}(\theta)\right\|_{F} \leq\left|T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta)\right|\left\|\nabla T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta)\right\|_{F}+\left\|\nabla T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta) \nabla T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta)\right\|_{F}
\end{gathered}
$$

Note that $T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta)=N^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \exp \left\{(\theta-\phi)^{\prime} X_{i \bullet}\right\}$. Since $\Theta$ is compact, and $\theta \mapsto e^{\theta^{\prime} y} \in \mathbb{R}$ is

continuous, the map admits a lower and upper bound, say $\left[l_{y}, u_{y}\right]$. Here, the dependence of $l, u$ on $y$ is implicit. However, since $y$ is also bounded as is the case in our setting, and the map $y \mapsto e^{a^{\prime} y}$ is continuous, there exists $l=\inf _{y} l_{y}>-\infty$ and $u=\sup _{y} u_{y}<\infty$. Thus, $T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta) \geq l$. Also,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\nabla T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta)\right\|_{F} & =N^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{N}\left\|\exp \left\{(\theta-\phi)^{\prime} X_{i \bullet}\right\} X_{i \bullet} X_{i \bullet}^{\prime}\right\|_{F} \\
& \leq N^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \exp \left\{(\theta-\phi)^{\prime} X_{i \bullet}\right\}\left\|X_{i \bullet} X_{i \bullet}^{\prime}\right\|_{F} \\
& \leq u \sqrt{(p+m)}
\end{aligned}
$$

since elements of the $(p+m) \times 1$ vector $X_{i \bullet}$ are either 0 or 1 . Next, $\left\|\nabla T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta)\right\|_{2} \leq$ $N^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \exp \left\{(\theta-\phi)^{\prime} X_{i \bullet}\right\}\left\|X_{i \bullet}\right\|_{2} \leq u \sqrt{(p+m)}$. Hence,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\nabla T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta) \nabla T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta)\right\|_{F} & \leq\left\|\nabla T_{N}^{\left(\nabla_{\theta} z\right)}(\theta)\right\|_{2}\left\|\nabla T_{N}^{(z)}(\theta)\right\|_{2} \\
& \leq N^{-1} u \sqrt{(p+m)} \sum_{i=1}^{N}\left\|\exp \left\{(\theta-\phi)^{\prime} X_{i \bullet}\right\} X_{i \bullet}\right\|_{2} \\
& \leq u^{2}(p+m)
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, we have that $T_{N}(\theta) \rightarrow \nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)$ almost surely and the sequence is equicontinuous on $\Theta$. Hence, $T_{N}(\theta) \rightarrow \nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)$ uniformly on $\Theta$ with probability 1 (Rudin et al., 1964, Exercise 7.16).
(II) $\lim _{\mathbf{t} \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{\mathbf{k}=1}^{\mathbf{t}} \gamma_{\mathbf{k}} \mathbf{E}_{\mathbf{k}}$ exists almost surely: First, note that $\left\|T_{N}(\theta)\right\|_{2}<\infty$. This is a consequence of the arguments presented above. Let $M_{t}=\sum_{k=1}^{t} \gamma_{k} E_{k}$ and $E_{0}=0$. Then $M_{k}$ is an $\mathcal{F}$-martingale with $\mathcal{F}=\cap_{t=1}^{\infty} \mathcal{F}_{t}$. Moreover,

$$
\sum_{t=1}^{\infty} \mathbb{E}\left[\left\|M_{t}-M_{t-1}\right\|_{2}^{2} \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}\right] \leq \sum_{t=1}^{\infty} \gamma_{t}^{2} \mathbb{E}\left[\left\|E_{t}\right\|_{2}^{2} \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}\right]<\infty
$$

This implies that $\lim _{t \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \gamma_{k} E_{k}$ exists almost surely.
(C) The estimator $\mathbf{T}_{\mathbf{N}}(\theta)$ is asymptotically uniformly unbiased: First note that $T_{N}(\theta)$ is a vector. We recall that if $x_{n}$ is a sequence in $\mathbb{R}^{p}$, then $x_{n} \rightarrow x \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$ iff $\Psi\left(x_{n}\right) \rightarrow$

$\Psi(x)$ for all linear functional $\Psi$. Now, $\left|\Psi\left(T_{N}(\theta)\right)\right| \leq\|\Psi\|\left\|T_{N}(\theta)\right\|$, which is bounded following similar arguments as above. Hence, by the dominated convergence theorem,

$$
\lim _{N \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{E}\left[\Psi\left(T_{N}(\theta)\right)\right] \rightarrow \mathbb{E}\left[\lim _{N \rightarrow \infty} \Psi\left(T_{N}(\theta)\right)\right]=\Psi\left(\nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)\right)
$$

Since $\Psi\left(\mathbb{E}\left[T_{N}(\theta)\right]\right)=\mathbb{E}\left[\Psi\left(T_{N}(\theta)\right)\right]$, we have that:

$$
\lim _{N \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{E}\left[T_{N}(\theta)\right] \rightarrow \nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)
$$

Moreover, by uniform convergence of $T_{N}(\theta)$ to $\nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)$, for every $\epsilon>0$, there exists $N(\epsilon)$ such that:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left\|\mathbb{E}\left[T_{N}(\theta)-\nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)\right]\right\|_{2} & =\left\|\int\left[T_{N}(\theta)-\nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)\right] \prod_{i=1}^{N} p_{\phi}\left(X_{i \bullet}\right) d X_{i \bullet}\right\|_{2} \\
& \leq \int\left\|T_{N}(\theta)-\nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)\right\|_{2} \prod_{i=1}^{N} p_{\phi}\left(X_{i \bullet}\right) d X_{i \bullet} \\
& \leq \epsilon
\end{aligned}
$$

for all $\theta$. An immediate consequence of this is that there exists a sequence of Monte Carlo sample sizes $\left\{N_{t}\right\}_{t \geq 1}$ such that $\left\|R_{t}\right\|_{2}=\left\|\mathbb{E}\left[T_{N_{t}}\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right]-\nabla_{\theta} \log z\left(\theta^{(t)}\right)\right\|_{2} \rightarrow 0$ as $t \rightarrow \infty$.
(D) The mean field satisfies $\mathbf{m}(\theta)=\nabla_{\theta} \log \mathbf{p}_{\theta}(\mathbf{v})$ : By Fisher's identity, we have:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\nabla_{\theta} \log p_{\theta}(\mathbf{v})=\frac{\nabla_{\theta} p_{\theta}(\mathbf{v})}{p_{\theta}(v)}=\frac{\nabla_{\theta} \sum_{\mathbf{h}} p_{\theta}(\mathbf{v}, \mathbf{h})}{p_{\theta}(v)} & =\mathbb{E}\left[\nabla_{\theta} \log p_{\theta}(\mathbf{v}, \mathbf{h}) \mid \mathbf{v}, \theta\right] \\
& =\nabla_{\theta} g(\mathbf{v} ; \theta, \theta)-\nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)
\end{aligned}
$$

(E) $\mathbb{E}\left[\left\|\mathbf{h}\right\|_{2}^{2} \mid \theta, \mathbf{v}\right]<\infty$ : This follows from the fact that $\|\mathbf{h}\|_{2}^{2}$ is bounded and $\mathbf{h} \mid \mathbf{v}, \theta$ also follows an Ising distribution.

The conclusion of the theorem follows from Delyon et al. (1999, Theorems 2 and 5) by noting that the complete data model is a member of the exponential family satisfying the regularity conditions for these theorems and due to (A), (B), (C), (D).

# S. 2 A Simple Accept-Reject Sampler for $p_{\theta}(\cdot)$ 

Generating samples from a Boltzmann distribution, of which PEGMs are special cases, remains a challenge; especially without resorting to computationally expensive MCMC techniques. However, our approach also accomplishes this goal. Specifically, for a given $\theta$, suppose we simulate $Y \sim p_{\phi}(\cdot)$, where $\phi=\operatorname{diag}(\theta)$. This is cheap, and does not require MCMC. Moreover, $z(\phi)$ is analytically available. Next, recall, $p_{\theta}(x)=q_{\theta}(x) / z(\theta)$. Thus, an accept-reject sampler for $p_{\theta}(\cdot)$ consists of the following two steps:

1. Simulate $Y \sim p_{\phi}(\cdot)$
2. Accept $Y$ with probability $r=q_{\theta}(Y) /\left\{M p_{\phi}(Y)\right\}$ where $M$ is such that $q_{\theta}(Y)<$ $M p_{\phi}(Y)$ for all $Y$.

Thus, $M$ must be chosen to satisfy the criterion:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\exp ( & \left.\sum_{j} \theta_{j} Y_{j}+\sum_{j \neq k} \theta_{j k} Y_{j} Y_{k}\right)<M \exp \left(\sum_{j} \theta_{j} Y_{j}\right) / z(\phi) \\
& \text { i.e., } \exp \left(\sum_{j \neq k} \theta_{j k} Y_{j} Y_{k}\right)<M z(\phi)^{-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

However, a simple choice of $M$ is available for several PEGMs. For example, in a Poisson graphical model, all off-diagonal elements of a valid $\theta$ are negative, and one may take $M z(\phi)^{-1}=1$, i.e., $M=z(\phi)$. Similarly, for Ising, where $Y_{j}=\{0,1\}$ for all $j$, a simple choice is $\left\{M: M z(\phi)^{-1}>\exp \left(p^{2} \max _{j k} \theta_{j k}\right)\right\}$. Other, less obvious choices of $M$ may result in better average acceptance probabilities. We do not explore the details in this work.

## S. 3 Algorithmic Details for Section 4
## S.3.1 Tuning $\lambda$ in (8) and model selection

Here we describe how the value of the tuning parameter $\lambda$ is selected in (8). Generally, pseudo-likelihood methods have a regression structure in that the likelihood of $X_{j} \mid X_{-j}$ is

a generalized linear model for PEGMs. As a result, out-of-sample prediction is typically used for tuning parameter selection. This is, however, not the case when a full-likelihood analysis is implemented. In our work, we instead consider the out-of-sample log-likelihood to select the value of $\lambda$ given estimated $\hat{\theta}_{\lambda}$ is available for a grid of values of $\lambda:\left[\lambda_{l}, \lambda_{u}\right]$. Specifically, we divide the observed data randomly into $K$-folds, of which $K-1$ folds are used to obtain $\hat{\theta}_{\lambda}$ for each value of $\lambda$. The log-likelihood $\ell\left(\hat{\theta}_{\lambda}\right)$ is computed on the remaining fold. The process is repeated for each fold, and we choose $\hat{\theta}_{\lambda}$ to be our estimator for which we obtain the maximum out-of-sample log-likelihood. This generally results in improved Frobenius norm estimates of $\theta$ as reported in Table 1. However, it is well known that cross-validated estimates in penalized estimation procedures may provide sub-optimal performance in terms of model selection (Bühlmann and Van De Geer, 2011). To address this, we construct an estimator of $\theta$ that selects edges between nodes which are most often selected. Suppose, for $R$ choices of $\lambda$, we obtain estimates $\hat{\mathbf{S}}_{\lambda_{r}}=\left\{(j, k): \hat{\theta}_{\lambda_{r}, j k} \neq 0\right\}$. Define $I_{j k}^{r}=\mathbb{I}\left\{(j, k) \in \hat{\mathbf{S}}_{\lambda_{r}}\right\}$. Then, we estimate the structure of the graph $G$ by:

$$
\hat{\mathbf{S}}=\left\{(j, k): \frac{1}{R} \sum_{r=1}^{R} I_{j k}^{r}>\pi_{t h r},\right\}
$$

where $0<\pi_{t h r}<1$. The procedure closely resembles stability selection (Meinshausen and Bühlmann, 2010), except here we do not perform subsampling. Our experiments with and without subsampling resulted in similar performance. Hence, we omit that step. For the threshold $\pi_{t h r}$, we use 0.6. Results from this choice are reported under the MCC column in Table 1. For fair comparison, we also implemented this structure learning method with pseudo-likelihood based approaches.

# S.3.2 HMC for PEGMs 

Suppose we observe iid data $\mathbf{X}=\left(X_{1 \bullet}, \ldots, X_{n \bullet}\right)$ from some $\operatorname{PEGM}(\theta)$. Consider the following prior structure over $\theta: \pi(\theta)=\int\left[\prod_{j \leq k} \pi\left(\theta_{j k} \mid \tau\right)\right] g(\tau) d \tau$, i.e. the elements $\theta_{j k}$

are conditionally independent given a global shrinkage parameter $\tau$. The posterior is then:

$$
\pi(\theta \mid \mathbf{X}) \propto\left[\prod_{i=1}^{n} \frac{q_{\theta}\left(X_{i \bullet}\right)}{z(\theta)}\right] \pi(\theta)
$$

We make two simplifying assumptions. First, we fix $\tau=1$, noting that our procedure can be easily incorporated in the general case when $\tau \sim g$ with an additional layer of sampling. Second, we assume that the convexity of $\Theta$ can be represented as $C(\theta) \geq 0$ for a suitable choice of a differentiable $C(\theta)$.

Suppose $\pi\left(\theta_{j k}\right)$ admits the marginal representation $\pi\left(\theta_{j k}\right)=\int \pi\left(\theta_{j k} \mid \rho_{j k}\right) \pi\left(\rho_{j k}\right) d \rho_{j k}$, with respect to some latent variables $\rho_{j k}$, and $\pi\left(\theta_{j k} \mid \rho_{j k}\right)$ is differentiable. This is indeed the case for any prior that is a scale mixture of Gaussian. Then samples from the augmented posterior $\pi\left(\theta,\left\{\rho_{j k}\right\}_{j \leq k} \mid \mathbf{X}\right)$ can be obtained by employing a Gibbs sampler that iterates between sampling from $\pi\left(\theta \mid\left\{\rho_{j k}\right\}_{j \leq k}, \mathbf{X}\right)$ and $\pi\left(\left\{\rho_{j k}\right\}_{j \leq k} \mid \theta, \mathbf{X}\right)$. We use a HMC sampler to sample from $\pi\left(\theta \mid\left\{\rho_{j k}\right\}_{j \leq k}, \mathbf{X}\right)$ and sample $\rho_{j k}$ 's in a block since these are conditionally independent. To ensure that the HMC sampler lives within $C(\theta)$, we adopt the constrained HMC sampler from Betancourt (2011). A full description of the transition operation of the sampler is provided in Algorithm S. 1 where we write $\theta=\operatorname{vech}(\theta)$ with a slight abuse of notation. Let $U(\theta)$ denote the negative of the logarithm of $\pi\left(\theta \mid\left\{\rho_{j k}\right\}_{j \leq k}, \mathbf{X}\right)$ up to proportionality constants, i.e. $U(\theta)=-\sum_{i=1}^{n} \log q_{\theta}\left(X_{i \bullet}\right)+n \log z(\theta)-\sum_{j \leq k} \log \pi\left(\theta_{j k} \mid \rho_{j k}\right)$, and $\nabla_{\theta} U(\theta)$ denote its gradient which is available following Proposition 3.1 and due to the assumption that $\pi\left(\theta_{j k} \mid \rho_{j k}\right)$ is differentiable. The new state generated according to Algorithm S. 1 is accepted with the standard Metropolis correction (Neal, 2011, Section 5.3.2.1).

Then, the model can be seen to be a PEGM with density $p_{\theta}(x)=q_{\theta}(x) / z(\theta)$ with:

with standard properties of a multivariate Gaussian density yielding:

$$
z(\theta)=(2 \pi)^{p / 2} \operatorname{det}(\theta)^{-1 / 2}, \quad \nabla_{\theta} z(\theta)=-\frac{1}{2}(2 \pi)^{p / 2} \operatorname{det}(\theta)^{-1 / 2} \theta^{-1}, \quad \nabla_{\theta} \log z(\theta)=-\frac{1}{2} \theta^{-1}

and, for $\phi=\operatorname{diag}(\theta)$, one obtains:

$$

$$

# S.4.3 A comparison of RBM and BM representational power 

Existing literature on training performance of the CD algorithm and its other versions focus mostly on benchmark datasets. Nonetheless, in this section we report the results of CD training versus the proposed approach in controlled simulation experiments. We compare the quality of the corresponding density estimate in terms of the total variation distance: $\operatorname{TV}\left(p_{\theta_{0}}, p_{\theta}\right)=\sum_{\mathbf{v} \in\{0,1\}^{p}}\left|p_{\theta_{0}}(\mathbf{v})-p_{\hat{\theta}}(\mathbf{v})\right|$ where the dimension of $\theta_{0}$ is the data generating value of the parameter and $\hat{\theta}$ is the estimate obtained from the two methods, noting that the dimensions of $\theta_{0}$ and $\hat{\theta}$ might be different given that the number of hidden variables is unknown in reality. We consider two cases $(p, m)=(2,2)$ and $(p, m)=(3,4)$ and set the sample size $n=1000$. Elements of the true data generating $\theta_{0}$ are set to 0 with probability 0.5 and are drawn from Uniform $[-1,1]$ with probability 0.5 , respecting the bipartite structure of the graph. When implementing CD we set $k=1$, although we did not notice any significant difference in results for $k$ up to 10 . We report in Table S. 3 results averaged over 50 replications where we abbreviate the proposed method here by FL (for full likelihood). All hyperprameters for training for the two algorithms are kept same, including the step size and convergence criteria. Two key observations can be made

from the results. First, for increasing values of the number of hidden variables $m$, the fit is better, which is expected. Second, the performance of FL is better compared to CD in almost all cases, albeit by a small margin.

We next consider experiments where we study the representational power of RBMs to that of BMs. Since both method learn distributions of visible variables, we want to investigate whether allowing connections within layers as in BM (see also Figure 1), leads to similar or better learning power for a smaller number of hidden variables. For this we consider two situations $p=3,5$ which is the dimension of the visible variable. We generate the visible variables from a multivariate probit model where $y_{j}=\mathbb{I}\left(z_{j}>0\right)$ and $z=\left(z_{1}, \ldots, z_{p}\right)^{\mathrm{T}} \sim \mathrm{N}(0, \Sigma)$. We set $\Sigma=(\Sigma)_{i j}$ with $\Sigma_{i i}=1$ and $\Sigma_{i j}=0.5, i \neq j=$ $1, \ldots, p$. This model is often used to capture dependent multivarite binary data (Ashford and Sowden, 1970; Chakraborty et al., 2023). We fix the sample size of the visible variables to $n=1000$, and fit RBM and BM to the data letting the number of hidden variables $m$ vary between $6-12$ for $p=3$, and $10-18$ for $p=5$, with increments of 1 . Ideally, with enough hidden variables, RBMs should be able to approximate the data generating distribution (Le Roux and Bengio, 2008). We show the total variation distance between the true distribution and the fitted distribution from both models in Figure S.3, which reveals that BM achieves better approximation to the distribution of the visible variables with a fewer number of hidden variables, at least for this data generating distribution. Indeed, the gain in approximation for BM is almost $50 \%$ for $p=3$ and $33 \%$ for $p=5$. The trade-off is the computation time. The key bottleneck of training a full BM is the fact that the conditional distribution of the hidden variables depend on the corresponding visible variables which is not the case for RBMs. This allows for much faster training of RBMs. While a theoretical investigation into the representational power of BM is beyond the scope of this work, we hope that our numerical experiments serve as a platform for further investigation into the properties of a full BM.

abstract:
Probabilistic graphical models that encode an underlying Markov random field
are fundamental building blocks of generative modeling to learn latent
representations in modern multivariate data sets with complex dependency
structures. Among these, the exponential family graphical models are especially
popular, given their fairly well-understood statistical properties and
computational scalability to high-dimensional data based on pseudo-likelihood
methods. These models have been successfully applied in many fields, such as
the Ising model in statistical physics and count graphical models in genomics.
Another strand of models allows some nodes to be latent, so as to allow the
marginal distribution of the observable nodes to depart from exponential family
to capture more complex dependence. These approaches form the basis of
generative models in artificial intelligence, such as the Boltzmann machines
and their restricted versions. A fundamental barrier to likelihood-based (i.e.,
both maximum likelihood and fully Bayesian) inference in both fully and
partially observed cases is the intractability of the likelihood. The usual
workaround is via adopting pseudo-likelihood based approaches, following the
pioneering work of Besag (1974). The goal of this paper is to demonstrate that
full likelihood based analysis of these models is feasible in a computationally
efficient manner. The chief innovation lies in using a technique of Geyer
(1991) utilizing the tractable independence model underlying an intractable
graphical model, to estimate the normalizing constant, as well as its gradient.
Extensive numerical results, supporting theory and comparisons with
pseudo-likelihood based approaches demonstrate the applicability of the
proposed method.
